"""
mkt-context — Numbers chapters 16–18
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-numbers-16-18.py

Ch 16: Korah's rebellion — challenge to Mosaic-Aaronic authority, censer test,
       earth swallowing Korah/Dathan/Abiram, fire consuming 250, bronze censer
       altar-covering, Aaron's censer stopping the plague
Ch 17: Aaron's budding staff — almond as sign, staff before the ark
Ch 18: Priestly and Levitical duties — priests bear sanctuary guilt, Levites as
       buffer, priestly portions (most holy, firstfruits, firstborn), YHWH as
       Aaron's inheritance, tithe-of-tithe system, covenant of salt

ANE context notes:
- Korah's challenge is about priestly access, not theology — the 250 are civic
  leaders seeking liturgical function; ANE parallels in royal manipulation of
  temple appointments (Egypt, Mesopotamia)
- The almond (sheqed) is first-blooming tree in Israel; root = shoqed (watching),
  cf. Jer 1:11-12 — YHWH as the 'watching' God over covenant
- 'Covenant of salt' (18:19) — salt as preservation/permanence symbol; irrevocable
  covenants in the ANE; Mesopotamian salt-oath ceremonies
- The Levitical tithe chain (10% → 1%) is unique in the ANE; Mesopotamian and
  Egyptian temple revenue went directly to temple institutions, not through
  a distributed mediating class
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / f'mkt-{source}' / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / f'mkt-{source}' / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

NUMBERS = {
  "16": {
    "1": "<p>The rebellion is introduced with a genealogy: Korah son of Izhar son of Kohath son of Levi. Korah is a Kohathite Levite — from the highest-status Levitical family, the one tasked with carrying the ark and the most holy objects (Num 4:4-15). His revolt is not from the margins but from within the established liturgical structure. Dathan and Abiram are Reubenites — a significant coalition: the premier Levitical clan joins with descendants of Jacob's firstborn. The rebellion has both priestly-class and firstborn-tribe dimensions.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The 250 are not a mob but Israel's civic elite: <em>nesi'ei edah</em> (leaders of the congregation), <em>qri'ei mo'ed</em> (called/invited to the assembly — the formal term for covenant representatives), <em>anshei shem</em> (men of name/renown). This is an organized challenge by Israel's leadership class. In ANE contexts, high-status temple officials or civic nobles sometimes challenged priestly appointments when they felt their prerogatives were being exceeded. The coalition represents a structural challenge to Moses's and Aaron's combined political-religious authority.</p>",
    "3": "<p>'The whole congregation is holy, every one of them, for the LORD is in their midst' — the challenge's theological framing. The claim is not false: Exod 19:6 does call Israel a 'kingdom of priests' and a 'holy nation.' But Korah's company draws an illegitimate conclusion: that universal holiness eliminates the need for differentiated priestly roles. The argument is a misapplication of a genuine theological truth. In the ANE, the tension between royal appointment of priests (as in Egypt and Mesopotamia) and hereditary priestly privilege was well-known; Korah's challenge parallels moments when non-priestly elites attempted to usurp cultic functions.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Moses's response to the challenge is to fall facedown — prostration before YHWH, not before the rebels. The posture signals two things simultaneously: submission to YHWH's judgment (which Moses is confident will vindicate him) and the gravity of what is happening. Moses does not rebuke Korah immediately with words; he falls before YHWH. The narrative models the proper response to illegitimate authority challenges: not human self-defense but deference to divine judgment.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'Tomorrow morning YHWH will show who is his and who is holy, and will bring that one near to himself.' The censer test is postponed to the next morning — the delay serves both narrative and theological purposes. Israel must wait on YHWH's timing rather than seeking an immediate resolution. The phrase <em>asher yivchar bo yaqriv elav</em> — 'the one he chooses he will bring near' — recapitulates the central vocabulary of priestly election: <em>bachar</em> (choose), <em>qarav</em> (draw near). Priestly proximity to YHWH is a matter of divine choice, not human qualification or claim.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Moses instructs Korah's company to prepare censers (<em>machtot</em>) — the bronze fire-pans used for transporting incense coals. The censer was intimately associated with the most sacred moment of the liturgical year: the high priest's incense-burning inside the Holy of Holies on Yom Kippur (Lev 16:12-13), where the incense cloud was meant to screen the priest from YHWH's presence. By inviting the 250 to bring censers, Moses is creating a test that will expose them to the direct divine encounter for which they are not authorized — and for which they are not prepared.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'The man YHWH chooses shall be the holy one' — the censer test is a divine oracle, not a human competition. The test is elegant in its simplicity: YHWH does not need to argue; he will simply show. <em>Rav lakhem b'nei levi</em> — 'you have gone too far, sons of Levi' — Moses turns the rebels' own phrase back on them (v.3 uses <em>rav lakhem</em> against Moses; now Moses uses it against Korah). The reversal is pointed: the accusation of excess applies to the accusers themselves.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'Hear now, sons of Levi' — Moses addresses Korah and the Levites directly and separately from Dathan and Abiram. The Levitical challenge is distinct from the Reubenite challenge: Korah wants priestly access; Dathan and Abiram challenge Mosaic political authority (vv.12-14). Moses addresses each grievance on its own terms. The direct appeal to Korah as a Levite acknowledges the legitimacy of Levitical service even as Moses denies the legitimacy of Korah's further ambitions.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'Is it too small a thing for you that the God of Israel has separated you from the congregation of Israel to bring you near to himself?' — Moses articulates what the Levitical vocation actually is: <em>havdil</em> (to separate, distinguish), <em>qarav</em> (to draw near). The Levites have already been brought near to YHWH — nearer than any other tribe. They serve the tabernacle, they bear the holy vessels, they stand between Israel and YHWH's holiness. To count this as a small thing is to despise the very gift of nearness that YHWH has given them.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'He has brought you near, and all your fellow Levites with you. And yet you seek the priesthood too?' The phrase <em>uvikashtem gam kehunah</em> — 'you are also seeking the priesthood' — identifies the specific object of Korah's ambition. The priesthood (<em>kehunah</em>) is distinct from Levitical service: the priests burn incense, enter the sanctuary, eat the most holy portions. The Kohathites' proximity to the most holy objects had apparently whetted rather than satisfied their desire for priestly access. Moses diagnoses ambition masquerading as egalitarian theology.</p>",
    "11": "<p>'Therefore it is against the LORD that you and all your company have gathered.' Moses cuts to the theological core: the rebellion is not against him personally but against YHWH's appointment. <em>Ki veHoshem attem noalim</em> — 'for what is Aaron, that you grumble against him?' Moses depersonalizes the attack: he and Aaron are not the targets; YHWH's structure is. This is a significant theological move: attacks on legitimate authority in Israel are attacks on the God who appointed that authority. The challenge is ultimately theocentric, not political.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Moses summons Dathan and Abiram for a separate confrontation — but they refuse to come. 'We will not come up' — <em>lo na'aleh</em>. The refusal to come before Moses is itself an act of rebellion: in Israel's covenantal structure, summoning before the covenant mediator was equivalent to a divine summons. Their refusal is not just impolite; it is a statement that they no longer recognize Moses's authority to summon them at all.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Dathan and Abiram's accusation is remarkable: they describe Egypt as 'a land flowing with milk and honey' — the phrase YHWH uses throughout the wilderness narrative for Canaan. They have reversed the theological geography: Egypt (the land of bondage) is reimagined as the place of abundance; Canaan (the promised land) is the threat of death. This is a grotesque inversion — a measure of how far the rebels' perception has drifted from YHWH's framing of the exodus. The ANE context of slavery in Egypt, with its Nile agriculture, may lie behind the romanticization: Egypt's irrigated fields were genuinely fertile.</p>",
    "14": "<p>'You have not brought us into a land flowing with milk and honey, nor have you given us fields and vineyards.' The accusation is technically true — Israel is still in the wilderness. But the force of the covenant promise has not been rescinded; Israel's situation is a consequence of their own faithlessness at Kadesh (Num 13-14). Dathan and Abiram suppress this context. They also accuse Moses of seeking to 'rule over us' — <em>ki tishtarer aleinu</em> — delegitimizing his authority entirely. The charge is that the exodus was a leadership project serving Moses's ambitions, not YHWH's salvation.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Moses's anger is expressed through prayer: 'Do not accept their offering.' <em>Al tefan el-minchatam</em> — do not turn toward their grain offering. The imprecation echoes Cain and Abel (Gen 4:3-5): YHWH's acceptance or rejection of an offering is the final verdict on the offerer. Moses then provides his own defense: 'I have not taken one donkey from them, nor have I harmed any one of them.' The list of potential abuses he has NOT committed defines the standard of legitimate leadership: a leader who has not extracted wealth or done personal harm. The defense anticipates Samuel's similar declaration in 1 Sam 12:3.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The confrontation is scheduled for the next day before YHWH — Moses, Aaron, Korah, and the 250 all appearing at the tent of meeting. The divine presence is the intended arbiter: YHWH will adjudicate through the censer test itself. The staging is significant: the tent of meeting is the site of covenant encounter, and the confrontation is being brought formally into YHWH's presence rather than adjudicated by human authority. The test will be a liturgical act, resolved by divine fire.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Each of the 250 takes a censer — 250 censers plus Moses's and Aaron's. The scale is specified deliberately: 250 unauthorized censers vs. Aaron's single legitimate one. In ancient Israelite practice, the number of censers in use before YHWH was tightly controlled; unauthorized censers had precedent in Nadab and Abihu (Lev 10:1-2), who offered 'strange fire' and were consumed. The 250 are effectively reenacting that transgression at massive scale.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The 250 and Korah assemble at the entrance of the tent of meeting with fire in their censers and incense on them — the prescribed liturgical form. They have done everything correctly except one thing: they are not authorized. The narrative emphasizes their technical compliance to highlight the distinction between form and authorization. In the ANE, unauthorized individuals performing legitimate cultic forms were sometimes punished harshly by temples; the issue was not the correctness of the ritual but the legitimacy of the practitioner.</p>",
    "19": "<p>'Korah gathered the whole congregation against them at the entrance of the tent of meeting.' The rebellion reaches its climax: Korah has organized the entire assembly into opposition. Then YHWH's glory appears to the whole congregation. The <em>kavod YHWH</em> (the glory of the LORD) is the visible manifestation of divine presence — a theophanic phenomenon associated with the cloud and fire of the tabernacle. Its appearance is the divine answer to the assembly's challenge: YHWH himself arrives to adjudicate.</p>",
    "20": "<p>YHWH's first response to the theophany is a command to Moses and Aaron: separate yourselves from this congregation. The command mirrors YHWH's instruction at Sodom (Gen 18:20-19:12) and the Korah account's earlier parallel with the golden calf episode (Exod 32:9-10), where YHWH instructs Moses to stand aside while judgment falls. The pattern of divine wrath requiring a righteous remnant's separation is a consistent feature of YHWH's judicial acts throughout Israel's wilderness narrative.</p>",
    "21": "<p>'Separate yourselves from this congregation so that I may consume them in an instant.' <em>Rega'</em> — in a moment, instantaneously. The same word appears in Exod 33:5 and Num 17:45 — YHWH's capacity for instantaneous judgment is a theological marker of his absolute sovereignty. The threat to consume the entire congregation (not just Korah's company) reflects how seriously YHWH takes communal solidarity with rebellion: those who passively acquiesce to a challenge to divine authority share in its guilt.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Moses and Aaron fall facedown and intercede: 'O God, God of the spirits of all flesh' — the same title used in Num 27:16 (Moses's prayer for a successor) — 'shall one man sin and you be angry with the whole congregation?' The intercession appeals to YHWH's justice: corporate punishment for individual sin violates the principle of proportional judgment. Significantly, both the rebel Korah and the intercessors Moses and Aaron use prostration as their posture before YHWH. But the meaning differs: Korah's company prostrates in a liturgical act; Moses and Aaron prostrate in intercessory prayer.</p>",
    "23": "<p>YHWH responds to the intercession — a partial modification: the whole congregation will not be destroyed, but the specific rebels' households will be targeted. The divine response to Moses and Aaron's intercession is not total capitulation but a narrowing of judgment scope. The pattern of covenantal intercession modifying divine judgment (cf. Gen 18:22-33; Exod 32:11-14; Amos 7:1-6) recurs throughout Israel's relationship with YHWH: the mediator's prayer genuinely affects the scope of divine action.</p>",
    "24": "<p>'Tell the congregation to move away from the dwellings of Korah, Dathan, and Abiram.' The separation of innocent from guilty is enacted spatially: physical distance from the rebels' tents is required. The instruction presupposes that proximity to judgment is dangerous — contact with those under divine curse is itself a risk. This is the spatial-moral logic of purity and contagion applied to divine judgment: the rebels' tents become zones of danger that must be evacuated.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Moses goes in person to Dathan and Abiram — they would not come to him (v.12), so he goes to them. The elders of Israel accompany Moses, giving his action communal authority. Moses's willingness to approach those who have rebelled against him and refused to appear before him is itself a form of leadership: he brings the judgment to them rather than allowing their refusal to stall the process. The elders as witnesses ensure that the judgment, when it comes, will be publicly credible.</p>",
    "26": "<p>'Move away from the tents of these wicked men' — <em>anshei harasha'im ha'eleh</em> — 'and touch nothing that belongs to them, lest you be swept away in all their sins.' The verb <em>tissafu</em> (be swept away) is the same root used of being gathered to one's people at death (Num 27:13) and of divine collection-for-judgment. To touch the rebels' possessions is to be caught up in the sphere of their guilt. The prohibition has ANE parallels in devotion (<em>cherem</em>) practice, where the possessions of those under divine curse were themselves cursed and could not be touched without contamination.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The congregation separates; Dathan and Abiram stand defiantly at the entrances of their tents — with their wives, children, and infants. The detail is theologically difficult: the families are present and will be consumed. Ancient Israelite judicial practice sometimes extended corporate punishment to households for the head's crime (cf. Achan, Josh 7:24-26). The theological rationale is not that the children were guilty but that the rebellion's consequences fell on the entire social unit the rebel led. The families' presence also intensifies the tragedy of the coming judgment.</p>",
    "28": "<p>'By this you shall know that the LORD has sent me to do all these works, and that it has not been of my own accord.' The coming judgment is explicitly framed as a divine sign vindicating Moses's prophetic commission. <em>Ki lo millibi</em> — 'for it was not from my heart.' Moses is not seeking personal vindication; he is seeking YHWH's vindication. The formula 'you shall know that YHWH has sent me' connects to the Exodus <em>yada'</em> theme: YHWH acts in history so that Israel (and others) may know him as the acting God.</p>",
    "29": "<p>If the rebels die a natural death — <em>kmot kol ha'adam</em>, the common death of all humanity — then Moses was not sent by YHWH. This is a falsifiability test: Moses is publicly staking his prophetic authority on a specific, observable outcome. The willingness to set up a verifiable test is itself a feature of authentic prophecy in Israel (Deut 18:21-22). The contrast with ordinary death creates anticipation: something other than ordinary death is about to occur.</p>",
    "30": "<p>'But if the LORD creates something entirely new' — <em>uvri'ah YHWH beriah</em>. The word <em>beri'ah</em> (a creation, something uniquely brought into existence) derives from <em>bara</em> (H1254, the word for God's creative act in Gen 1:1). What is about to happen is not natural but genuinely new: a theophanic creation event. The earth will open its mouth and swallow them — they will go down alive into Sheol. This is both a geological-physical event and a theological statement: YHWH's judgment penetrates beneath the ordered surface of creation into the realm of death itself.</p>",
    "31": "<p>'As soon as he finished speaking all these words, the ground under them split apart.' The immediacy of fulfillment — the ground opens the moment Moses finishes speaking — validates the prophetic word in the most compressed possible way. There is no delay between the spoken word and the event: YHWH's action is coterminous with Moses's speech. This pattern (word → immediate fulfillment) is the signature of prophetic authority in Israel, and its extreme compression here marks the event as a definitive divine verdict.</p>",
    "32": "<p>The earth swallows Korah, Dathan, Abiram, their households, and all the people belonging to Korah. The scope of the judgment is the household — the basic social unit of Israelite life. The phrase <em>et kol ha'adam asher l'korah</em> — 'all the people who belonged to Korah' — may refer to Korah's extended household network or followers. The Sheol-descent of the living is without direct ANE parallel in its theological specificity: these rebels do not merely die; they are actively received into the realm of the dead while still alive.</p>",
    "33": "<p>'They went down alive into Sheol, they and all who belonged to them. The earth closed over them, and they perished from the midst of the assembly.' <em>Sheol</em> (H7585) — the realm of the dead in Hebrew thought: a dim underworld of shades, separated from YHWH's presence (cf. Ps 6:5; 88:3-6; Isa 38:18). The text does not describe Sheol's geography but its theological character: it is separation from the covenant community and from YHWH. For the rebels to enter it alive is for their judgment to be both physical and theological — a literal descent into the consequence of separation from YHWH that they had been living in spiritual form.</p>",
    "34": "<p>'All the Israelites around them fled at their cry, for they said: Lest the earth swallow us also!' The community's terror is not cowardice but theological recognition: YHWH's judgment has demonstrated his holiness in the most dramatic possible way. The flight ensures there are survivors to witness and transmit the event. The cry of the people — <em>pen tivcla'enu ha'aretz</em> — mirrors the rebels' own fate and makes explicit what Israel has learned: the earth is an instrument of YHWH's justice that can consume the living.</p>",
    "35": "<p>'Fire also came out from the LORD and consumed the 250 men who were offering incense.' A separate judgment for the separate component of the rebellion: while Dathan and Abiram are swallowed (the Reubenite-political dimension), the 250 are consumed by fire (the priestly-liturgical dimension). The divine fire recalls Nadab and Abihu (Lev 10:2: 'fire came out from before the LORD and consumed them'). The censers they carried — instruments of the unauthorized incense offering — survive to become the altar covering of vv.38-40.</p>",
    "36": "<p>YHWH immediately addresses the aftermath: the censers must be retrieved from among the burning. The distinction is notable — the fire from YHWH consumed the men but left the censers, which are now described as <em>holy</em> (v.37-38) — they have been brought near to YHWH, however illegitimately, and now belong to the sacred sphere. The sacred cannot simply be discarded; it must be reabsorbed into the sanctuary system appropriately.</p>",
    "37": "<p>Eleazar the priest (not Aaron — Aaron was involved in stopping the plague, v.46) is commanded to retrieve the censers. The coals must be scattered away from the site — the fire itself was holy. The censers are to be hammered (<em>ritzu</em>) into flat sheets — a metallurgical act of transformation. The instruments of rebellion become, through the priest's action, material for the sanctuary. The process mirrors Israel's broader theological pattern: what was used for transgression can be repurposed for covenantal service.</p>",
    "38": "<p>'The censers of these men who sinned at the cost of their own lives' — <em>benapshot'am</em> — 'at the price of their lives.' The phrase underscores that the 250 paid with their lives for their act. The censers are hammered into flat sheets to overlay the altar. The altar covering becomes a permanent <em>zikkaron</em> (memorial/reminder) — a physical inscription in metal of the lesson: no unauthorized person shall approach to offer incense before YHWH. The bronze becomes a public teaching tool built into the structure of the sanctuary itself.</p>",
    "39": "<p>Eleazar carries out the command: he takes the bronze censers and has them hammered into altar plating. The execution is precise and immediate — as with all Mosaic commands, completion is noted. The censers have thus completed a strange journey: Levitical instruments used in an unauthorized priestly act, destroyed by divine fire, now permanently affixed to the altar as a warning against the very act they were used for. The altar itself becomes a commentary on the rebellion it survived.</p>",
    "40": "<p>'A reminder to the Israelites that no unauthorized person — not of Aaron's line — should come near to offer incense before the LORD, so that he would not become like Korah and his company' — <em>ka'asher dibber YHWH b'yad moshe lo</em> — 'as the LORD had said through Moses to him.' The memorial formula closes the account: the bronze plating on the altar is a permanent exegetical object, visible to every worshipper approaching the altar, encoding the theological lesson in the most durable medium available — fired bronze from the instruments of judgment.</p>",
    "41": "<p>'But the next day the whole congregation of Israel grumbled against Moses and Aaron.' The rebellion was yesterday; the memorial altar covering is freshly installed; and Israel grumbles again. The speed of the recurrence is part of the narrative's point: divine judgment does not produce lasting repentance in a people whose fundamental orientation is not transformed. The charge against Moses and Aaron is grotesque: 'You have killed the people of YHWH.' The rebels who challenged YHWH's order are reframed as YHWH's people killed by illegitimate authority — the moral inversion is complete.</p>",
    "42": "<p>When the congregation assembles against Moses and Aaron, they turn toward the tent of meeting and the cloud has covered it — the glory of YHWH appears again. The theophanic reappearance in direct response to fresh grumbling signals that YHWH takes the repeated rebellion as seriously as the original. The cloud covering the tent is a double sign: YHWH's presence is protective of the sanctuary and its authorized servants, and ominous toward those who challenge them.</p>",
    "43": "<p>Moses and Aaron go to the front of the tent of meeting — the appropriate response to a divine appearance: they present themselves at YHWH's threshold. The contrast with the congregation's behavior is sharp: when YHWH appears, Moses and Aaron approach; the congregation had assembled <em>against</em> Moses and Aaron but now face a more immediate presence. Their charge against Moses is about to be overtaken by a direct divine response.</p>",
    "44": "<p>A second 'Get away from this congregation so I may consume them in an instant' — the divine command repeats exactly from v.21. The repetition is significant: the same threat, the same formula, the same urgency. The pattern of divine judgment → intercession → modified outcome is being replayed. YHWH's patience is not inexhaustible, but the pattern of covenantal intercession remains operative. Moses and Aaron's response will again be to fall facedown in intercession.</p>",
    "45": "<p>'Get away from this congregation so that I may consume them in an instant.' Moses and Aaron fall facedown — the intercessory posture. But now there is no time for extended prayer: the plague has already begun. The gap between divine command and divine action is closing. The narrative's urgency increases: intercession must be accompanied by action.</p>",
    "46": "<p>Moses's instruction to Aaron is immediate and specific: take the censer, add fire from the altar (not strange fire), put incense on it, go quickly to the congregation and make atonement. The censer Aaron is instructed to use carries the legitimate altar fire — the opposite of the 250's unauthorized fire. The same instrument that condemned the rebels (censer + incense) is now deployed by the authorized priest for the community's salvation. The irony is deliberate: the instrument whose misuse caused judgment is now, in authorized hands, the instrument of atonement.</p>",
    "47": "<p>Aaron runs into the middle of the congregation — <em>vayarutz el-tokh haqqahal</em> — the plague had already begun. The running signals urgency: Aaron is literally racing against the plague's spread. He makes atonement (<em>yekhapper</em>) for the people and stands between the dead and the living — <em>bein hametim ubein hakhayim</em>. This image of priestly mediation is one of the most powerful in the Torah: Aaron standing in the space between death and life, his censer creating an atoning boundary that the plague cannot cross.</p>",
    "48": "<p>'He stood between the dead and the living, and the plague was stopped.' <em>Vata'atzar hamaggerfah</em> — the plague was restrained/stopped. The priestly act of intercession-through-incense halts a divine judgment already in progress. The image of standing between dead and living will echo through Israel's prophetic tradition (cf. Ezek 22:30: YHWH seeks someone to 'stand in the breach') and ultimately in the NT's presentation of Christ as the great high priest who 'always lives to intercede' (Heb 7:25).</p>",
    "49": "<p>14,700 died in the plague — 'besides those who had died in the matter of Korah.' The precise number is given: YHWH's judgments are not vague but specific and bounded. The number records both the severity of the judgment (greater than many battles) and its limitation (it stopped). The 14,700 are a discrete, counted body — the plague's toll is inscribed in Israel's memory with the precision of a census.</p>",
    "50": "<p>Aaron returns to Moses at the entrance of the tent of meeting after the plague has stopped. The return to the tent — the site of YHWH's covenant presence — closes the episode. The entire sequence (rebellion → earth swallowing → fire → memorial altar covering → fresh grumbling → plague → priestly intercession → plague stopped) has been contained within the sanctuary's gravitational field: everything happens at or near the tent of meeting, and everything resolves at its entrance. The tent remains the center of Israel's covenantal life through all the turbulence.</p>"
  },
  "17": {
    "1": "<p>The staff-test episode follows immediately after the plague — YHWH's judgment has silenced but not persuaded the grumblers (v.12-13 will show their despair). The new revelation formula opens a different kind of divine response to the authority challenge: where ch.16 demonstrated YHWH's negative verdict through judgment, ch.17 will demonstrate YHWH's positive designation through miraculous growth. The two responses together — judgment and vindication — constitute the complete divine answer to Korah's challenge.</p>",
    "2": "<p>One staff per ancestral house (<em>beit av</em>) — twelve staffs for twelve tribes, one for each leader (<em>nasi</em>). The staff (<em>matteh</em>, H4294) is the same word as 'tribe' in Hebrew — the leader's staff is the embodiment of tribal identity. The test uses the most ordinary object of leadership to carry the most extraordinary sign: from a dead piece of wood, YHWH will produce life.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Aaron's name is written on the Levitical staff — one staff for Levi as for every other tribe, but with Aaron specifically named. The naming individualizes the test: it is not Levitical authority in general that will be vindicated but Aaron's specifically. The staff-writing is an act of ownership and designation: the name on the staff identifies whose claim YHWH will adjudicate. The twelve staffs, with names, function as a kind of written oracle that YHWH will answer.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'Place them in the tent of meeting before the covenant document' — <em>lifnei ha'edut</em>. The staffs are placed in YHWH's immediate presence: the space before the ark and the tablets of the covenant is the most holy site in the Israelite world. The test's site is deliberately chosen: the divine sign will emerge from within YHWH's own dwelling space. No human can manipulate the result; the staffs are placed before YHWH and left for him to act upon.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'The man I choose — his staff will sprout.' <em>Ufarach matteh ha'ish asher evchar bo</em>. The sign is specific: growth. Not decay, not fire, not splitting — but the biological sign of life: <em>parach</em> (H6524, blossom, sprout, break out). In Hebrew idiom, <em>parach</em> is associated with renewal, the righteous flourishing (Ps 92:12; Isa 35:1-2). YHWH will demonstrate his choice through the sign of life emerging from death — from a staff that has been cut from its tree and is, by rights, dead wood. 'I will rid myself of the Israelites' grumbling against you' — the sign is explicitly directed at the grumbling problem identified throughout the wilderness narrative.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Moses collects twelve staffs — one per leader, with Aaron's for Levi. The staffs are ordinary leaders' staffs: the same kind that every tribal <em>nasi</em> would carry. The ordinariness of the objects makes the sign more astonishing — YHWH does not use exotic sacred instruments but the everyday symbols of human authority.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Moses places the staffs before YHWH in the tent of the covenant (<em>ohel ha'edut</em>). The tent of the covenant/testimony — the tabernacle named for the two tablets of testimony it houses — is the site of the divine act. The placement 'before the LORD' is the key spatial designation: the staffs are within YHWH's direct presence, subject to his action alone.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'The next day Moses went into the tent of the covenant, and there was Aaron's staff — representing the house of Levi — had sprouted: it budded, produced blossoms, and bore ripe almonds.' The Hebrew is remarkably precise: <em>vayifra' vayatzetz tzitz vayyigmal shqedim</em> — it budded, put out blossoms, and produced ripe almonds. Three stages of growth in a single overnight: bud → blossom → ripe fruit. This is not merely germination but accelerated full-cycle growth.</p><p>The almond (<em>shaqed</em>, H8247) is the first tree to bloom in the land of Israel — typically in late January or early February, before its leaves appear. Its name in Hebrew (<em>shaqed</em>) is connected to the verb <em>shaqad</em> (H8245, to watch, to be awake/alert). YHWH tells Jeremiah (1:11-12): 'I see a staff of almond (<em>shaqed</em>)... I am watching (<em>shoqed</em>) over my word to perform it.' The almond is the sign of divine watchfulness and initiative — YHWH watching over the covenant to keep it.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Moses brings all twelve staffs out for all the Israelites to see. Each leader takes his own staff. The public display of the staffs ensures that the sign is witnessed by the whole community: there can be no doubt about which staff budded, no suspicion of manipulation. The twelve staffs displayed together make the contrast maximally visible — eleven dead sticks and one living tree.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'Put Aaron's staff back before the covenant document, to be kept as a sign against the rebels' — <em>lemishmeret le'ot libn'ei meri</em>. The budded staff joins the covenant document (the tablets) and later the jar of manna (Exod 16:33-34) as items kept within or near the ark as permanent covenantal signs. The staff's preservation links Aaron's priestly authority directly to the Sinai covenant: his priesthood is not a human appointment but a covenant institution. The <em>benei meri</em> (children of rebellion) are warned by the preserved sign that YHWH's choice is irrevocable.</p>",
    "11": "<p>'Moses did so; he did just as the LORD commanded him.' The completion formula. Moses's obedience is the consistent frame of the narrative: regardless of the community's challenge to his authority, he executes YHWH's commands precisely. The formula's brevity stands in contrast to the community's elaborate rebellion; faithfulness to YHWH's commands is simple even when the context is turbulent.</p>",
    "12": "<p>'We are dying, we are perishing, we are all lost.' The community's response to the signs is not repentance but despair: <em>gava'nu avadnu kulanu avadnu</em> — three synonymous declarations of perishing in rapid succession. The threefold expression is a literary-emotional intensification. The signs have demonstrated YHWH's holiness beyond any reasonable doubt, and Israel's response is existential terror: if approaching YHWH is this dangerous, survival seems impossible.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'Anyone who comes near the tabernacle of the LORD shall die. Are we all going to die?' The question — rhetorical, despairing — captures Israel's theological crisis at the end of the Korah narrative. The proximity to YHWH that Korah's company sought by demanding priestly access turns out to be genuinely dangerous. The Israelites' terror is theologically appropriate: drawing near to the holy God without proper mediation is fatal. The cry ends the Korah episode and sets up ch.18's clarification of the mediating structure that makes safe cohabitation with YHWH's holiness possible.</p>"
  },
  "18": {
    "1": "<p>YHWH addresses Aaron directly — not through Moses — for the only time in the wilderness narrative. The direct address underscores the personal nature of what follows: Aaron's priestly responsibility is between him and YHWH. 'You and your sons and your ancestral house shall bear the guilt of sins against the sanctuary' — <em>avon hamiqddash</em>. The priesthood is not merely a privilege but a burden: the priests absorb the guilt that would otherwise fall on Israel as a whole when sanctuary violations occur. The priests' acceptance of this burden is what makes the sanctuary safe for Israel to approach.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The Levites are to join Aaron as assistants — <em>yilavu alekha</em> (they shall be joined to you) — a wordplay on <em>Levi</em> (attached, joined, Levi's name explained in Gen 29:34). The Levites' structural role as a buffer between Israel and the sanctuary is now explicitly mandated: they absorb the holiness danger that would otherwise expose ordinary Israelites to fatal contact with the sacred sphere. The organization is concentric: Israel → Levites (outer court service) → Priests (inner sanctuary and altar).</p>",
    "3": "<p>'They shall fulfill their duties to you and to the whole tent, but they shall not come near the furnishings of the sanctuary or the altar, lest both they and you die.' The Levites serve Moses-ward and tent-ward but not sanctuary-furnishings-ward or altar-ward. The specific exclusions precisely map the zones of holiness: the inner sanctuary and the altar are priestly-only domains. The death penalty for crossing these boundaries (for both Levite and priest — 'lest both they and you die') reflects the absolute nature of the sacred gradations in Israel's tabernacle geography.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'They shall join you and keep the charge of the tent of meeting — all the service of the tent — and no unauthorized person shall come near you.' The Levites' service creates a human buffer between Israel and the sanctuary's most dangerous zones. The phrase <em>zar lo yiqrav aleikhem</em> — 'no stranger/outsider shall come near you' — uses <em>zar</em> (outsider, unauthorized person), the same term used in v.7 for those whose approach is punishable by death. The Levites' presence enforces the access gradients of the sanctuary.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'You shall be responsible for the sanctuary and the altar, so that wrath does not fall on the Israelites again.' <em>V'lo yihyeh qetzef al b'nei yisrael od</em> — the motivation for the entire priestly-Levitical arrangement: the prevention of wrath. The wrath (<em>qetzef</em>, H7110) that fell in the plague of ch.16 must not recur. The structural arrangement of priests, Levites, and congregation is not merely organizational but soteriological: it is the mechanism by which Israel can coexist with YHWH's holiness without being consumed by it.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'Behold, I myself have taken your kinsmen the Levites from among the Israelites. They are given to you as a gift to the LORD, to serve at the tent of meeting.' <em>Nethunim nethunim hem l'kha</em> — 'given, given they are to you' — the double verb creating emphasis. The Levites are YHWH's gift to Aaron: divine provision for the priestly task. The phrase <em>la'avod et avodah</em> — 'to serve the service' — the redundancy emphasizing the wholeness of the Levitical vocation: their entire identity is service at the sanctuary.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'But you and your sons shall attend to your priestly duties for everything at the altar and within the veil, and you shall serve.' The priests' domain: the altar and everything within the veil — the full interior of the sanctuary including the Holy of Holies. <em>Avodah matanah etten et kehunat'khem</em> — 'I give your priestly service as a gift.' The priesthood is not earned but received: YHWH gives it as a gift. The <em>zar haqarev yumat</em> — 'the stranger who comes near shall be put to death' — grounds the access boundaries in the gravest possible sanction.</p>",
    "8": "<p>YHWH now specifies the priestly portions — the material provision for those who have no land inheritance. The priestly share of the offerings is YHWH's direct provision for the priests' material needs. The formula <em>ani hineh natati lekha</em> — 'I myself, behold, I have given to you' — is emphatic: YHWH is personally providing for the priesthood through the offerings. This reframes the priestly system as a divine welfare arrangement: the priest who serves YHWH does not go unprovided for.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The most holy portions (<em>qodesh qodashim</em>) — what is not burned up from fire offerings, grain offerings, sin offerings, and guilt offerings — belong to Aaron and his sons. <em>Qodesh qodashim</em> — holy of holies, the superlative form — reserved for the priests themselves and to be eaten in the most holy place (v.10). The three main sacrifice types (grain/sin/guilt) contribute portions to the priestly table. The priestly portion is literally 'what comes off the altar' — the portion that YHWH retains from the offering system goes directly to his servants.</p>",
    "10": "<p>'In the most holy place you shall eat it; every male shall eat it. It is most holy for you.' The spatial restriction for eating the most holy portions — <em>baqodesh qodashim tokhalenu</em> — means the priests eat within the sanctuary precincts. Only male priests are permitted (the most restricted category). The repeated <em>qodesh qodashim hu lekha</em> — 'it is most holy for you' — is both privilege and warning: the food carries the same holiness-danger as the sanctuary itself and must be treated with corresponding care.</p>",
    "11": "<p>A second category of priestly portions: the contribution of wave offerings (<em>terumah</em> of <em>tenufah</em>). These are given to the priests and their households — both male and female family members, unlike the most holy portions. <em>Kol tahor b'veit'kha yokhal oto</em> — 'everyone who is clean in your household may eat it.' The extension of priestly portions to the whole clean household makes the priesthood a family vocation: the priest's purity provisions encompass his entire domestic unit.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The <em>bikkurim</em> (firstfruits) portions go to the priests: the best of the oil, the best of the wine, the best of the grain — <em>kol chelev</em> (all the fat/best). The principle is consistent throughout the priestly portion system: the best goes to YHWH, and what goes to YHWH goes to his servants. The agricultural calendar's firstfruits — the very first and finest of each crop — belong to the sanctuary before any household consumption. This structure ensures YHWH's acknowledgment as the land's owner precedes Israel's enjoyment of the land's produce.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'The first ripe produce of all that is in their land, which they bring to the LORD, shall be yours.' The priestly portion of <em>bikkurim</em> encompasses all first produce regardless of type. <em>Kol tahor b'veit'kha yokhal oto</em> — the household purity restriction again: the priestly household eats these portions, but only those who are ritually clean. The priestly table is the intersection of divine provision and personal purity.</p>",
    "14": "<p>'Everything in Israel that is <em>cherem</em> (devoted to destruction) shall be yours.' The <em>cherem</em> category — objects or persons placed under total divine devotion (Lev 27:28-29) — reverts to the priests. The extension of priestly control over <em>cherem</em> property is significant: the most extreme sanctification category (that which is wholly given to YHWH and cannot be redeemed) passes through the priestly system. The priest mediates even the most absolute forms of covenantal dedication.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Every firstborn of all flesh — human or animal — belongs to YHWH and thus to his priests. The firstborn principle runs through the entire priestly system: the first of everything (firstborn, firstfruits, first tenth) belongs to YHWH. Human firstborns and firstborns of unclean animals are redeemed; clean animal firstborns are sacrificed. The system acknowledges YHWH's claim on the first of all life while building in redemption mechanisms for what cannot be literally dedicated (human beings, economically necessary unclean animals).</p>",
    "16": "<p>The redemption price for human firstborns: five shekels of silver by the sanctuary shekel, from one month old. The sanctuary shekel (<em>b'shekel haqodesh</em>) is a standardized weight used for sacred payments. Five shekels is also the valuation of a person aged one month to five years in the Lev 27:6 scale. The one-month threshold before redemption is required (before one month, infant death was too common for the system to apply) — a practical pastoral accommodation within a theological framework.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The firstborn of a cow, sheep, or goat cannot be redeemed — they are holy (<em>qadosh hem</em>). Their blood is sprinkled on the altar and their fat burned as a fire offering — the standard sacrificial procedure for peace offerings. These clean livestock firstborns belong to the altar and to YHWH directly; no redemption price is permitted. The distinction between redeemable (human, unclean animal) and non-redeemable (clean livestock) firstborns creates a graduated system of sacred dedication.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The meat of the unredeemable firstborns belongs to the priests — the breast of the wave offering and the right thigh. The specified portions (breast + right thigh) are the priestly share of the peace offering in general (Lev 7:31-34), establishing that the firstborn offering follows the same distribution pattern as the standard fellowship sacrifice. The system's consistency — same portions, same formulas across different offering types — reflects the deliberate ordering of the entire sacrificial framework.</p>",
    "19": "<p>'All the contributions of the holy gifts that the Israelites offer to the LORD I give to you and your sons and daughters as a perpetual ordinance.' <em>Brit melach olam</em> — 'a covenant of salt forever.' Salt in the ANE was the symbol of permanence and incorruptibility: it preserved food and thus became the material sign of an enduring agreement. Salt covenants are attested in Mesopotamian treaty traditions; in the Hebrew Bible, salt is associated with covenant durability (2 Chr 13:5; Ezra 4:14 — 'eating the salt of the palace' = loyal covenant obligation). The priestly provisions are as permanent and irrevocable as salt.</p>",
    "20": "<p>'You shall have no inheritance in their land, nor shall you have any portion among them — I am your portion and inheritance among the Israelites.' <em>Ani chelqkha v'nachalatekha</em> — 'I am your portion and your inheritance.' This is one of the Torah's most theologically condensed statements. The priests receive no land allotment in Canaan (confirmed in Josh 13:14, 33; 18:7). Their material security rests entirely on YHWH's provision through the offering system. The formula transforms the apparent deprivation (no land) into a superior provision: YHWH himself is the priest's inheritance. In ANE thought, divine favor was the highest possible form of wealth; YHWH as Aaron's estate outranks any land grant.</p>",
    "21": "<p>To the Levites: all the tithes (<em>kol ma'aser</em>) in Israel as their inheritance. The tithe is one-tenth of Israel's agricultural and livestock production. The Levites have no land but they have the tithe of those who work the land — a sustainable, nationwide economic provision tied to Israel's agricultural productivity. <em>Tachat avodatam</em> — 'in return for their service' — the tithe is compensation for sacred labor. The Levites' work at the tent of meeting is compensated by the very Israelites whose access to YHWH the Levites make possible.</p>",
    "22": "<p>'The Israelites must not come near the tent of meeting, lest they bear sin and die.' The access prohibition is restated in the wake of ch.16-17: Korah's rebellion and its aftermath have demonstrated what happens when unauthorized people approach the sanctuary. The prohibition is not punishment but protection: the graduated access system (Israel → Levites → priests) keeps Israelites from the mortal danger of approaching YHWH's holiness without proper mediation.</p>",
    "23": "<p>'Only the Levites shall serve at the tent of meeting, and they shall bear responsibility for any offenses against it.' The Levites bear a double burden: they serve and they absorb guilt. <em>Vehem yissu avonam</em> — 'they shall bear their iniquity' — Levitical service includes the absorption of any impurity or offense committed by the community in relation to the sanctuary. The priest and Levite are guilt-bearers for the community they serve: their office requires them to stand in the place of judgment that would otherwise fall on the people.</p>",
    "24": "<p>'For the tithe of the Israelites, which they present as a contribution to the LORD, I have given to the Levites as their inheritance.' The tithe as <em>nachalah</em> (inheritance/holding) mirrors the priestly inheritance formula of v.20 — both priests and Levites receive a form of <em>nachalah</em> from YHWH rather than land. The Levites' inheritance is economic (tithe), the priests' is relational (YHWH himself). Therefore the Levites have no <em>nachalah</em> in land among the Israelites: they are provided for through a different mechanism.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The tithe-of-tithe legislation is introduced by a new revelation formula — YHWH speaks to Moses, who will transmit to the Levites. The chain of command (YHWH → Moses → Levites) reflects the Levites' structural position: they are not addressed by YHWH directly but through the Mosaic mediatorial chain. The tithe-of-tithe system creates the priests' income: the Levites pass 10% of what they receive to the priests, just as Israel gives 10% of its produce to the Levites.</p>",
    "26": "<p>'When you receive from the Israelites the tithe that I have given you as your inheritance, you shall present a contribution from it to the LORD — a tithe of the tithe.' <em>Ma'aser min hamma'aser</em> — the phrase establishes the nested structure clearly. The Levites are not exempt from contributing to the sacred economy simply because they receive from it; they too must give from what they have received. The principle that recipients of YHWH's provision give a portion back to YHWH applies at every level of the sacred hierarchy.</p>",
    "27": "<p>'Your contribution shall be credited to you as though it were the grain of the threshing floor and the produce of the winepress.' The tithe-of-tithe is treated equivalently to the firstfruits offering of an ordinary Israelite farmer. The Levites, who receive their income not from a field but from tithes, are nevertheless brought into the same sacrificial framework as any Israelite agriculturalist: their tithe-of-tithe is as valid an offering as grain from a literal threshing floor. The system's equity ensures that no member of Israel's sacred economy is structurally exempted from covenantal giving.</p>",
    "28": "<p>'So you shall also present a contribution to the LORD from all your tithes that you receive from the Israelites, and from it you shall give the LORD's contribution to Aaron the priest.' The contribution flows from Israelite → Levite (full tithe) → priest (tithe-of-tithe), with YHWH as the ultimate recipient at every level. Aaron the priest is named specifically: the tithe-of-tithe reaches the authorized priestly line. The system's architecture ensures that the highest-grade recipient — the priest who enters the sanctuary — receives the highest-grade portion (the best tenth of the tenth).</p>",
    "29": "<p>'Out of all the gifts you receive, you shall present every contribution owed to the LORD from the very best of it — the <em>chelev</em> (fat/best) of it, the sacred portion from it.' <em>Chelev</em> (H2459) in sacrificial contexts always means the best: just as the fat portions of the sacrifice are burned for YHWH (Lev 3:16-17; 7:23), the best of the Levitical tithe is designated as the sacred portion. The system insists on quality throughout: the Levites do not pass on the residue after keeping the best; they give the best to the priests and keep the rest for themselves.</p>",
    "30": "<p>'When you have presented the best of it, the remainder shall be counted to the Levites as the produce of the threshing floor and the winepress.' After giving the sacred best (the tithe-of-tithe to the priests), the Levites may treat the remaining nine-tenths as ordinary income. The remainder is theirs to consume freely, credited as an agricultural income equivalent. The system preserves the distinction between sacred (the tenth, given to the priests) and common (the rest, kept by the Levites) while making the Levites' material provision fully adequate.</p>",
    "31": "<p>'You and your households may eat it anywhere, for it is your payment for your service at the tent of meeting.' The Levites' portion is their salary: <em>sakar</em> (H7939, wages, payment). Unlike the most holy priestly portions (which must be eaten within the sanctuary), the Levites' income may be consumed anywhere. The freedom of location reflects the Levites' intermediate status: holier than ordinary Israelites (service at the tent) but less restricted than priests (who eat within the sanctuary precincts).</p>",
    "32": "<p>'You will bear no guilt because of it, once you have contributed the best of it. But do not profane the holy gifts of the Israelites, lest you die.' The chapter closes with a warning parallel to the access boundaries of vv.3 and 7: the Levites who give the priestly portion properly bear no guilt; but those who treat the holy gifts of the Israelites as common food (<em>lo techallelu et qodshei bnei yisrael</em>) face death. The sacred cannot be treated as common without fatal consequences. The ch.18 legislation is the structural answer to the ch.17 cry: 'Are we all going to die?' — no, because YHWH has built a system of graduated access and provision that makes coexistence with his holiness possible.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('context', 'numbers')
    merge_comm(existing, NUMBERS)
    save_comm('context', 'numbers', existing)
    for ch in ['16', '17', '18']:
        count = len(existing.get(ch, {}))
        print(f'ch {ch}: {count} verses in output')
    print('Numbers 16-18 context commentary written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
